    "abstract": "<jats:title>ABSTRACT</jats:title>\n                <jats:p>\n                  The COVID-19 pandemic caused by the Severe Acute Respiratory Syndrome Coronavirus-2 (SARS-CoV-2) is the defining global health emergency of this century. GC-376 is a M\n                  <jats:sup>pro</jats:sup>\n                  inhibitor with antiviral activity against SARS-CoV-2\n                  <jats:italic>in vitro</jats:italic>\n                  . Using the K18-hACE2 mouse model, the\n                  <jats:italic>in vivo</jats:italic>\n                  antiviral efficacy of GC-376 against SARS-CoV-2 was evaluated. GC-376 treatment was not toxic in K18-hACE2 mice and produced milder tissue lesions, reduced viral loads, fewer presence of viral antigen, and reduced inflammation in comparison to vehicle-treated controls, most notably in the brain in mice challenged with a low virus dose. Although GC-376 was not sufficient to improve neither clinical symptoms nor survival, it did show a positive effect against SARS-CoV-2\n                  <jats:italic>in vivo</jats:italic>\n                  . This study supports the notion that the K18-hACE2 mouse model is suitable to study antiviral therapies against SARS-CoV-2, and GC-376 represents a promising lead candidate for further development to treat SARS-CoV-2 infection.\n                </jats:p>",
